<subSubSection id="90C176B04331C91FFF2D0781D280BB48" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D864253B4331C91FFF2D0781D280BB48" blockId="2.[140,1108,589,1671]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294331C91FFF2D0781D00DBB02" bold="true" box="[185,304,765,791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis</emphasis>
A micropterous species of average size for 
<taxonomicName id="1FDB5EB84331C91FFC850781D2B1BB02" authorityName="Hope" authorityYear="1838" box="[785,908,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Philorhizus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294331C91FFC850781D2B1BB02" box="[785,908,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Philorhizus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with wide infuscated head, narrow pronotum, long-oval elytra yellowish with a wide dark transverse fascia at apical half and completely rounded humeri. Habitus, see 
<figureCitation id="40E039BE4331C91FFCE1063FD28ABB48" box="[885,951,835,861]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[140,174,1654,1676]" captionTargetBox="[169,1107,178,1626]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[126,1121,165,1638]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Philorhizus marggii n. sp., habitus, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2652725/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="90C176B04331C918FF2D061AD0D2BA50" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="description">
<paragraph id="D864253B4331C91FFF2D061AD0F5BBB0" blockId="2.[140,1108,589,1671]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294331C91FFF2D061AD07ABB95" bold="true" box="[185,327,870,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Description</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity id="1F2388DE4331C91FFE7C061BD348BB94" box="[488,629,871,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="3.7" metricValueMin="3.3" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="3.7" valueMin="3.3">3.3-3.7 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity id="1F2388DE4331C91FFD5B061AD24ABB94" box="[719,887,870,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.47" metricValueMax="1.56" metricValueMin="1.38" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="1.47" valueMax="1.56" valueMin="1.38">1.38-1.56 mm</quantity>
(
<typeStatus id="07609B994331C91FFC1C061AD2D0BB95" box="[904,1005,870,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">holotype</typeStatus>
<quantity id="1F2388DE4331C91FFC63061AD56EBB94" box="[1015,1107,870,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="3.6">3.6 mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity id="1F2388DE4331C91FFF2906F6D014BBB1" box="[189,297,906,932]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.48" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="1.48">1.48 mm</quantity>
, respectively).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D864253B4331C91FFF2D06D1D041BC62" blockId="2.[140,1108,589,1671]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Colour: Head (with exception of lighter clypeus) dark or light reddish piceous, mandibles, mouthparts, pronotum and appendages yellowish. Elytral basal half, apical margins and a large semicircular or almost square area around sutural angle testaceous, the remainder infuscated, forming a reddish piceous, wide, transverse, somewhat jagged fascia. The dark area bordering the suture extends slightly towards base of elytra.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D864253B4331C91FFF2D01FCD2E7BD3D" blockId="2.[140,1108,589,1671]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Head (
<figureCitation id="40E039BE4331C91FFE9C01FCD077BC8F" box="[264,330,1152,1178]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[140,174,1654,1676]" captionTargetBox="[169,1107,178,1626]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[126,1121,165,1638]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Philorhizus marggii n. sp., habitus, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2652725/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) large, almost as wide as pronotum (ratio PW/HW in males: 1.03- 1.06, 
<geoCoordinate id="BDEF43FC4331C91FFF5B01DED019BCAB" box="[207,292,1186,1214]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" precision="555" value="-1.05">Ø 1.05</geoCoordinate>
, 
<typeStatus id="07609B994331C91FFEA501DFD0A9BCA8" box="[305,404,1187,1213]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">holotype</typeStatus>
1.05; in female: 1.06). Eyes fairly large and flat, eye diameter about 2.3 to 3.0 times as long as rectilinearly narrowed tempora (seen in dorsal view). Antennae of medium length, slender, antennomeres 4-11 with dense and fairly fine setae except obligatory long apical setae (about as half as long as the latter).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D864253B4331C919FF2D004DD29BB912" blockId="2.[140,1108,589,1671]" lastBlockId="4.[140,1108,166,1179]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="5" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="40E039BE4331C91FFED6004CD0B5BD5F" box="[322,392,1328,1354]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[140,174,1654,1676]" captionTargetBox="[169,1107,178,1626]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[126,1121,165,1638]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Philorhizus marggii n. sp., habitus, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2652725/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) almost square (ratio PW/PL in males: 1.21-1.27, 
<geoCoordinate id="BDEF43FC4331C91FFC610052D572BD5F" box="[1013,1103,1326,1354]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" precision="555" value="-1.23">Ø 1.23</geoCoordinate>
, 
<typeStatus id="07609B994331C91FFF18002FD1CDBD78" box="[140,240,1363,1389]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">holotype</typeStatus>
1.27; in female: 1.36), widest at about end of anterior fourth (at insertion of lateral seta). Anterior margin moderately emarginate, anterior angles rounded, projecting slightly forward, from there slightly curved laterally till insertion of lateral seta (here somewhat angulate), from there basad almost rectangularly narrowed and weakly sinuate before posterior angles which are obtuse and angled strongly forward (at about length of antennomere 2), at insertion of seta weakly angulate. Base medially slightly emarginate, laterally to insertion of seta strongly curved (ratio PW/ PBaW in males: 1.21-1.27, 
<geoCoordinate id="BDEF43FC4331C91FFE480334D30BBE71" box="[476,566,1608,1636]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" precision="555" value="-1.24">Ø 1.24</geoCoordinate>
, 
<typeStatus id="07609B994331C91FFDD20336D397BE71" box="[582,682,1610,1636]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">holotype</typeStatus>
1.27, in female: 1.25). Lateral furrows at anterior angles narrow, becoming explanate toward base and continuing into large basal impression. Medial longitudinal impression deep, terminated at anterior and posterior transverse impression. Anterior transverse impression distinct, posterior transverse impression shallow and connecting both basal impressions.
</paragraph>
<caption id="8CA475B34330C91EFF18030AD350BE99" box="[140,621,1654,1676]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2652725/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" startId="3.[140,174,1654,1676]" targetBox="[169,1107,178,1626]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="D864253B4330C91EFF18030AD350BE99" blockId="3.[140,621,1654,1676]" box="[140,621,1654,1676]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294330C91EFF18030AD1F1BE99" bold="true" box="[140,204,1654,1676]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="1FDB5EB84330C91EFF46030AD0BCBE99" authority="Wrase &amp; Assmann, 2008" authorityName="Wrase &amp; Assmann" authorityYear="2008" box="[210,385,1654,1676]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Philorhizus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marggii" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294330C91EFF46030AD0BCBE99" box="[210,385,1654,1676]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Philorhizus marggii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F19C44524330C91EFE13030BD081BE99" box="[391,444,1655,1676]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, habitus, holotype.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="D864253B4337C919FF2D046CD001B9A2" blockId="4.[140,1108,166,1179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="40E039BE4337C919FE85046CD068B93F" box="[273,341,272,298]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[140,174,1654,1676]" captionTargetBox="[169,1107,178,1626]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[126,1121,165,1638]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Philorhizus marggii n. sp., habitus, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2652725/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) long-oval (ratio EL/EW in males: 1.38-1.41, 
<typeStatus id="07609B994337C919FC12046CD2D1B93F" box="[902,1004,272,298]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">holotype</typeStatus>
1.38; in female: 1.36; ratio EW/PW in males: 1.94-2.03, 
<geoCoordinate id="BDEF43FC4337C919FD5E044ED21CB958" box="[714,801,306,334]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" precision="555" value="-1.97">Ø 1.97</geoCoordinate>
, 
<typeStatus id="07609B994337C919FCBA044FD2A9B958" box="[814,916,307,333]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">holotype</typeStatus>
1.94; in female: 2.05) with completely rounded humeri, widest approximately at beginning of posterior fifth. Striae only suggested, becoming evanescent laterally. Hindwings reduced to small relicts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D864253B4337C919FF2D04BCD36ABA51" blockId="4.[140,1108,166,1179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Microsculpture mesh pattern on head in males consisting of weakly engraved isodiametric meshes on disc (somewhat more marked in the female), hence surface fairly shiny, on pronotum transverse and on elytra almost isodiametric in both sexes, moderately impressed, surface somewhat shiny.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D864253B4337C919FF2D0731D376BAE1" blockId="4.[140,1108,166,1179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Median lobe and internal sac structure (
<figureCitation id="40E039BE4337C919FDE70731D38BBA72" box="[627,694,589,615]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[140,174,1654,1676]" captionTargetBox="[150,1102,1292,1624]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[140,1109,1284,1634]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Philorhizus marggii n. sp. male genitalia, median lobe, lateral view, holotype. Scale bar 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2652727/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
): Relatively stout, with apical lamella small, evenly narrowed and apically rounded. Internal sac (in inverted condition) with a long winding, wide band of scales and thorns, which appears in lateral view in the middle part of the median lobe, reaching the apical part, and a short band of thorns, situated ventrally before the apical part.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D864253B4337C919FF2D0781D300BC8E" blockId="4.[140,1108,166,1179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294337C919FF2D0781D060BB02" bold="true" box="[185,349,765,791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Comparisons</emphasis>
In habitus and other characteristics (shiny head with weakly developed microreticulation, slender antennae, head wide with almost rectilinearly narrowed long tempora, pronotum very narrow, with posterior angles obtuse and angled strongly forward, micropterous, elytra with completely rounded humeri) similar to 
<taxonomicName id="1FDB5EB84337C919FE9306F6D34BBBB1" authority="(Meschnigg, 1934)" authorityName="Meschnigg" authorityYear="1934" baseAuthorityName="Meschnigg" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[263,630,906,932]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Philorhizus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294337C919FE9306F6D0B4BBB1" box="[263,393,906,932]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Ph. alpinus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="BC4A58CA4337C919FE0E06F6D350BBB1" author="Meschnigg J" box="[410,621,906,932]" journalOrPublisher="Entomologischer Anzeiger" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="65 - 68" part="14" refId="ref3773" refString="Meschnigg J (1934) Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Coleopteren vom Balkan. Entomologischer Anzeiger 14: 65 - 68." title="Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Coleopteren vom Balkan" type="journal article" year="1934">Meschnigg, 1934</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, described from the Aroania Mountains (
<collectingCountry id="A0CC65AB4337C919FF0006D1D1D1BBD2" box="[148,236,941,967]" name="Greece" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Greece</collectingCountry>
). The new species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="1FDB5EB84337C919FD7A06D1D250BBD2" baseAuthorityName="Meschnigg" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[750,877,941,967]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Philorhizus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294337C919FD7A06D1D250BBD2" box="[750,877,941,967]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Ph. alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its piceous head, by the elytra with a distinct, wide, dark transverse fascia at apical half which extends forward along the suture, omitting a large, testaceous semicircular or square area around the sutural angle, and by somewhat shorter tempora (while 
<taxonomicName id="1FDB5EB84337C919FC22016AD504BC25" baseAuthorityName="Meschnigg" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[950,1081,1046,1072]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Philorhizus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294337C919FC22016AD504BC25" box="[950,1081,1046,1072]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Ph. alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unicolorous, tempora almost as long as eye diameter). A comparison of the male genitalia cannot be given here, as the only specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="1FDB5EB84337C919FC830121D2AABC62" baseAuthorityName="Meschnigg" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[791,919,1117,1143]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Philorhizus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294337C919FC830121D2AABC62" box="[791,919,1117,1143]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Ph. alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
we were able to study was a female (see 
<bibRefCitation id="BC4A58CA4337C919FE3401FDD30DBC8E" author="Wrase DW" box="[416,560,1152,1179]" journalOrPublisher="Linzer biologische Beitrage" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="807 - 813" part="37" refId="ref3956" refString="Wrase DW (2005) Description of a new Philorhizus species from Greece and faunistic notes on other species previously described (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Lebiini). Linzer biologische Beitrage 37 (1): 807 - 813." title="Description of a new Philorhizus species from Greece and faunistic notes on other species previously described (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Lebiini)" type="journal article" year="2005">Wrase 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="8CA475B34337C919FF18030AD57DBE99" box="[140,1088,1654,1676]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2652727/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" startId="4.[140,174,1654,1676]" targetBox="[150,1102,1292,1624]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph id="D864253B4337C919FF18030AD57DBE99" blockId="4.[140,1088,1654,1676]" box="[140,1088,1654,1676]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294337C919FF18030AD1F7BE99" bold="true" box="[140,202,1654,1676]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="1FDB5EB84337C919FF45030AD0BDBE99" authority="Wrase &amp; Assmann, 2008" authorityName="Wrase &amp; Assmann" authorityYear="2008" box="[209,384,1654,1676]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Philorhizus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marggii" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="EAAFF9294337C919FF45030AD0BDBE99" box="[209,384,1654,1676]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Philorhizus marggii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F19C44524337C919FE12030BD084BE99" box="[390,441,1655,1676]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
male genitalia, median lobe, lateral view, holotype. Scale bar 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="D864253B4336C918FF2D05DAD0D2BA50" blockId="5.[140,1108,166,1038]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The new species can be differentiated from the other species occurring in the Balkan Peninsula [
